## How DI Works for MCP Tools

The SDK integrates directly with `Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection`:

| Mechanism | How it works |
|-----------|-------------|
| **Constructor injection** | Non-static `[McpServerToolType]` classes are resolved from DI. Register services normally (`AddHttpClient`, `AddSingleton`, etc.) and accept them via primary constructor. |
| **Method parameter injection** | Any method parameter whose type is registered in DI (or is `CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, `IProgress<>`) is injected automatically â€” it **won't** appear in the tool's JSON schema sent to the LLM. |
| **Schema-visible params** | Only parameters with `[Description]` are exposed to the LLM as tool inputs. |

**Key rule:** The SDK distinguishes tool inputs from injected services by type. `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, `CancellationToken`, and any DI-registered service are invisible to the LLM â€” only `string`, `int`, `bool`, etc. with `[Description]` become the tool's parameters.

This means you register services in `Program.cs` exactly as you would in any .NET app, and the MCP SDK handles wiring them into your tool classes at invocation time.
